NYC Covid-19 Data

We wish to do an initial analysis of some of the data which has been released for NYC. Then, we can extend this an fit a simple model for the spread of an infectious disease to both NYC and the entire US.

library(tidyverse)
library(sf)
library(tidycensus)
theme_set(theme_classic())

We had to download a different file and read it in to create this plot. It would be nice to not have to read an external file. Similarly, it might be interesting to compare this data to other demographic data which is observed at zip code level, such as income.

Zip codes can have very different numbers of people in them and Similarly, we have ACS data which also contains more granular information. Lets use the tidycensus package to access this.

Lets go back to looking at the NYC Covid data. We could extract lots of other variables for each zip code.

One important point is that zip codes vary a lot and to compare them directly is a bad idea. The number of people living in a zipcode can vary hugely. One simple way to correct for this would be to compute the number of positive tests with respect to this, for example the number of positive tests per 1000 people.

We can extract the population of each zip code also.

acs_2018_detailed <- get_acs(geography = "zcta",
                             variables = c(medincome = 
                                             "B19013_001",
                                           pop = "B01003_001",
                                           med_age = 
                                             "B01002_001"
                                           ),
                    year = 2018,geometry = FALSE)
## Getting data from the 2014-2018 5-year ACS
acs_variables <- acs_2018_detailed %>% pivot_wider(id_cols = c(GEOID,NAME),names_from = variable,
                                  values_from = estimate )

Then we want to combine the variables, the shape information and the Covid information.

nyc <- acs_2018 %>% 
  right_join(nyc_zip , by = c("zip"="MODZCTA")) %>%
  select(-c(variable,estimate,moe))

nyc <- nyc %>% left_join(acs_variables,by = "GEOID")

nyc %>% head()

Next we want to correct for population to better represent the underlying data. To do this we want to re-express the number of tests and the number of positive tests in terms of population. One way to do this is to compute the number of (positive) tests per thousand people.

nyc_sf <- nyc %>% 
  mutate(pop_1000 = pop/1000,
         test_1000 = Total/pop_1000,
         positive_1000 = Positive/pop_1000)


ggplot(nyc_sf) + geom_sf(aes(fill=positive_1000)) + 
  scale_fill_continuous(type = "viridis",name = "Positive Tests\n per 1k pop")

ggplot(nyc_sf) + geom_sf(aes(fill=test_1000)) + 
  scale_fill_continuous(type = "viridis",name = "Tests\n per 1k pop")

Now we can investigate relationships between the number of positive tests (per 1000 population) and demographic factors. These should be more correct.

The first thing we can investigate is the relationship between income and the number of tests.

nyc_sf %>% ggplot(aes(medincome,test_1000)) +

Similarly, we can look at the relationship between income and the number of positive tests.

A Simple SIR Model for NYC

One of the common ways that infectious diseases are modeled is using a SIR model. The population is divided into three groups at a given time:

  • Susceptible - people who could get infected
  • Infected - people who are currently infected
  • Recovered - people who have had the disease and have recovered.

We want to model \(C(t)\), the accumulated total cases at time \(t\). We can do this using a logistic model, which gives a differential equation of the form

\[ \frac{dC(t)}{dt} = r C(t)\left[ 1- \frac{C(t)}{K} \right], \] where \(r\) is the infection rate and \(K\) is the final size of the epidemic. Intuitively, this says that the rate of change of the total number of cases depends on the current cases, the infection rate, and how many more people can get infected. As \(C(t)\) grows close to \(K\), this rate has to slow down.

The solution to this differential equation is given by

\[ C(t) = \frac{K C_0}{C_0 +(K-C_0)\exp(-rt)}. \] Here \(C_0\) is the number of cases at \(t=0\), some starting point. We want to estimate \(K\) and \(r\) here for NYC currently.

We need to use data which gives the number of cases each day. Thankfully, this is also available onlne.

link_cases <- "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nychealth/coronavirus-data/master/case-hosp-death.csv"
nyc_cases <- read_csv(link_cases)
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   DATE_OF_INTEREST = col_character(),
##   CASE_COUNT = col_double(),
##   HOSPITALIZED_COUNT = col_double(),
##   DEATH_COUNT = col_double()
## )
nyc_cases %>% head()
nyc_cases$TIME <- c(0:(nrow(nyc_cases)-1))

nyc_time_data <- nyc_cases %>% 
  mutate(DATE_OF_INTEREST =
           as.Date(format(as.Date(DATE_OF_INTEREST,
                                    format= "%m/%d/%Y"),
                                   "20%y-%m-%d")),
         CUMUL_CASES = cumsum(CASE_COUNT)) %>%
  select(DATE_OF_INTEREST,TIME,CUMUL_CASES)
nyc_time_data %>% ggplot(aes(DATE_OF_INTEREST,CUMUL_CASES)) +
  geom_point() + theme_classic() + xlab("Date") +
  ylab("Total Cases")

logistic_model <- function(data) {
  data <- data %>% arrange(TIME)
  C_0 <- data$CUMUL_CASES[1]
  C_max <- data$CUMUL_CASES[nrow(data)]
  fit <-nls(
    formula = CUMUL_CASES ~ K / (1 + ((K - C_0) / C_0) * exp(-R * TIME)),
    data = data,
    start = list(K = 2 * C_max, R = 0.5),
    control = nls.control(minFactor = 1e-6, maxiter = 100)
  )
  return(fit)
}

fit_log<- logistic_model(nyc_time_data)

summary(fit_log)
## 
## Formula: CUMUL_CASES ~ K/(1 + ((K - C_0)/C_0) * exp(-R * TIME))
## 
## Parameters:
##    Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## K 1.459e+05  3.570e+03   40.86   <2e-16 ***
## R 3.690e-01  6.111e-03   60.39   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 17450 on 60 degrees of freedom
## 
## Number of iterations to convergence: 20 
## Achieved convergence tolerance: 7.921e-06
log_model_fit <- summary(fit_log)

resid <- tibble(index = 1:nrow(nyc_cases),
                vals = log_model_fit$residuals)

ggplot(resid,aes(index,vals)) + geom_point() + 
  theme_classic()

K_est <- coefficients(fit_log)[1]
r_est <- coefficients(fit_log)[2]
C_0 <- 2

nyc_time_data %>% ggplot(aes(TIME,CUMUL_CASES)) +
  geom_point() + theme_classic() + xlab("Date") +
  ylab("Total Cases") + 
  stat_function(fun = function(TIME)
     K_est / (1 + ((K_est - C_0) / C_0) *exp(-r_est * TIME)),
     colour = "red"
    )

So this model is not working particularly well. It is struggling to correctly capture the spread. There are many possible reasons for this.

  • The starting point. We are using the first day in this data set. Try changing this and see what happens.
  • NYC is so closely connected to the other regions around it in terms of people working in the city, etc. This model might work better on a country level.
  • A more flexible model would better model this. There are many extensions such as the SEIR, SIRD, and SEIS models.

The same model for the US

We can fit this type of model for the US instead.

Johns Hopkins also makes this data available online.

We want to rearrange this data so that we can more easily fit our model to it.

Lets first fit the model to the entire US. This would allow us to estimate the total number of infections we will see, \(K\).

tidy_us <- us_cases %>% pivot_longer(cols = contains("/"),names_to = "Date",values_to = "Count") %>% 
  mutate(Date = as.Date(format(as.Date(Date,
                                    format= "%m/%d/%Y"),
                                   "20%y-%m-%d"))) %>%
  select(Province_State,Date,Count)
tidy_us %>% head()
model_data <- tidy_us %>% group_by(Date) %>%
  summarise(Total = sum(Count)) %>%
  arrange(Date)

model_data %>% head()
model_data$TIME <- 1:nrow(model_data)

model_data %>% tail(n=10)

This is now in a nice tidy format that we can use for the model we have up above.

model_data$CUMUL_CASES = model_data$Total

fit_us<- logistic_model(model_data)

summary(fit_us)
## 
## Formula: CUMUL_CASES ~ K/(1 + ((K - C_0)/C_0) * exp(-R * TIME))
## 
## Parameters:
##    Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)

So this gives an estimate for \(R\) in the entire US of 0.170206 and a total number of cases of 1.069952310^{6}, which is currently less than the total number of cases. Lets look at the fit of this model.

K_est <- coefficients(fit_us)[1]
r_est <- coefficients(fit_us)[2]
C_0 <- 1



model_data %>% ggplot(aes(TIME,CUMUL_CASES)) +
  geom_point() + theme_classic()+
  ylab("Total Cases") + 
  stat_function(fun = function(TIME)
     K_est / (1 + ((K_est - C_0) / C_0) *exp(-r_est * TIME)),
     colour = "red"
    ) +xlab("Days since first case")

So this fit is much better than what we got for NYC alone, which we can also see by looking at the residuals.

us_model_fit <- summary(fit_us)

resid <- tibble(index = 1:nrow(model_data),
                vals = us_model_fit$residuals)

ggplot(resid,aes(index,vals)) + geom_point() + 
  theme_classic()

So there is still some pretty obvious structure here that we would like to not have. But it is an improvement.
